	"title": "Week 12",
	"content": "<h1 class=\"page-title\">Week 12</h1>\n  \n  <div id=\"todo-date-mount-point\"></div>\n  \n    <p><strong><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">Overview</span></strong></p>\n<div class=\"page\" title=\"Page 1\">\n<div class=\"section\" style=\"background-color: rgb(100.000000%, 100.000000%, 100.000000%);\">\n<div class=\"layoutArea\">\n<div class=\"column\">\n<p>Concept of equilibrium in capital markets, the capital asset pricing model, single-factor index models, idiosyncratic risk, market beta and alpha, the arbitrage pricing theory, multi-factor models of risk and returns&nbsp;</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n<p><strong><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">Learning Objectives</span></strong></p>\n<p>Upon completion of this week, you will be able to understand:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>how capital markets equilibrium constraint the relationship between risk and risk premium</li>\n<li>the main implication of the capital asset pricing model (CAPM)</li>\n<li>the distinction between absolute, market and idiosyncratic risk</li>\n<li>how to use index models to calculate market betas and alphas</li>\n<li>the limitations of the CAPM model and the role of other theories</li>\n<li>the implications of the Arbitrage Pricing Theory</li>\n<li>the multi-factor models of risk and return</li>\n<li>whether these asset pricing theories are supported by the data</li>\n</ul>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">Preparation for class</span></strong></p>\n<p>Mandatory reading:</p>\n<p>Lecture 5: <span class=\"instructure_file_holder link_holder instructure_file_link_holder\"><a id=\"81280790\" class=\"inline_disabled preview_in_overlay\" title=\"Link\" href=\"https://canvas.colorado.edu/courses/123249/files/81280790?wrap=1\" target=\"_blank\" data-canvas-previewable=\"true\" data-api-endpoint=\"https://canvas.colorado.edu/api/v1/courses/123249/files/81280790\" data-api-returntype=\"File\">lecture 5.pdf</a><a class=\"f